The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite well equipped, and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be allowed to wait any longer.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers are working at the most expensive in Europe is often reported on mobile.cz.
On the other hand, the telecommunications authority ČTÚ also confirmed that the price for an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradox - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a struggle.
Maybe it sounds paradox, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration of far more than 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to see that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) President of the Council, Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network has no more but many chances (by the way, he would probably not even find any frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market that led to a significant price reduction, which the traditional mobile operators had to respond to.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile there were similar voices on the market in the United Kingdom as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
Besides, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is Penta's financial group, which has U:phones in the Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually out of the way as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least half cheaper SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to set a non-climate target group.
This provider is specific to men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator firm of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could take place in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepíký also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively concentrated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile service providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look forward to it.
It will come to a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta Group of Finance.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not entirely entitled to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Its interest at the start of a virtual mobile phone provider has long been shown by the GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We have a great interest in offering not only fixed networks but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times come now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an unsurpassed wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no one has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršenů in his statement to the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds, in rare accordance with the declaration of O2: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "In the network of T-mobiles, by the end of the year, there will hardly be a virtual provider.
At this point, we had to have a specific offer to think in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepýký suggests: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we see from the customer's perspective as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a fall in profits.
So why should it be made easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the providers can draw on a string when it comes to something, it also sets the long slope and Her around the formation of U:phone.
The strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ went at the time when U:phone came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But now it's just U:phone as an argument why you shouldn't allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile radio market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new actor would place high demands on the market itself and in particular on its services."
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
But this related to this whole problem his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers," according to our request Kristian Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
The representatives of the suppliers would not be surprised by such a formulation.
From an authority representing consumer interests, including the fact that no one abuses its position on the market, this is more than a matter of concern.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual providers are working normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction do not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking that the almost already moving agreement of the three mobile operators is emerging from their reactions.
The question is whether it is really just a coincidence.
Just as the absolute same fuel price in the tankers is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a hard competition struggle.
"In this case, the Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive behaviour, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way on the matter.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so neither does he have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening the mobile phone market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the ČTù, since telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that he is necessarily taking a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting similarly.
Complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) are evidenced by the fact that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The decoupling of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, which distances the ÚOHS from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to implement the recently adopted telecommunications bill's novelty to extend CTU's competence in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must only know too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's gone if no one's looking.
The operation of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are also several in the Czech mobile networks, is neglected.
There are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but only in part of the public.
This is usually the case for companies operating in the multi-level marketing sector.
Own mobile telephone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke is that the company appears to be a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar sales.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then be engaged, which can lead to the termination of cooperation with the company concerned," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing is not happening to the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
These companies do not pay too much attention to their losses, while at the same time, unlike actual virtual suppliers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepýký points out some problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a very low percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone, so they cannot have complete access to it as the normal customers of mobile operators."
However, this should be at least unusual for the CTU alone.
There is also a further question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile service providers close their eyes before such a move, why do they block a virtual service provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has very strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to satisfy itself with the supplier's statement, they knew nothing about it and their business conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As already stressed in the text several times, the market entry of the virtual provider brought a significant price decline in the various services with it.
Practically in all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their origins from virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, or too strong a market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies in these moments are in a position to intervene, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot give the impression that incompetence in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information agrees and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile phone market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other stakeholders (to discriminate).
And then the Czechs will finally no longer call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
