The psychology of the area - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people in a competition, such as a rise in eBay, do not get beat and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto, while the others participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the sample were investigated through functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to earn money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured at the loss of the auction, where the opponent's area played a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase was explained by avoiding an overreaction of the contraction.
In order to undermine their thesis, the economists in the research group have also undertaken additional investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups against a partner should be provided under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and then made their interventions.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward, in case they come out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the case of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was that the emphasis was on one on the gain, while the other on the loss.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the group against "losing" were willing to make higher approaches than those in the control or profit group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These are the behaviours observed in auctions so far only based on the joy of winning, or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we have now prepared a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you visit your doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
However, the number of infected is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which means that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for hepatitis caused by various viruses, infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the errors and diseases differ.
Hepatitis viruses are reportedly spread to two different types: in hepatitis A and E by the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secretion, or storage).
Travellers are recommended for vaccination against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the healing can last up to two or three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die from hepatitis B-induced diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis each year.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only every 10 infected are treated with medicinal products.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected don't even know about their disease, since the bug destroys the liver cells in a home-made way - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control tests, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more frequent: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory study, it is advisable to seek the doctor for the first signs of unknown origin.
At the right time, the disease is healthy, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and preventing cancer.
The World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 is the first time that patients are represented worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
